This paper primarily focuses on the game-theoretic analysis of interactions between censors and censorship resistance systems, which falls under the category of computer security and cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also uses game theory to analyze optimal strategies for the censorship circumventor, which falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of data-channel protocols as cover for the CRS, which falls under the categories of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) and social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper discusses the impact of censorship on the equilibrium solutions, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CY).
